==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested in the 1520's.
* Borrowed from {{bor|en|la|accumulātus}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|accumulō||amass, pile up}}, formed from {{m|la|ad||to, towards, at}} + {{m|la|cumulō||heap}}, from {{m|la|cumulus||a heap}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/əˈkjuːmjʊˌleɪt/}}
* {{a|GA}} {{IPA|en|/ə.ˈkjum.jə.ˌleɪt/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-accumulate.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{hyph|en|ac|cu|mu|late}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[heap]] up in a [[mass]]; to [[pile]] up; to [[collect]] or bring [[together]] (either literally or figuratively)
#: ''He wishes to '''accumulate''' a sum of money.''
#: {{syn|en|amass|heap|hoard|store|Thesaurus:pile up}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[grow]] or [[increase]] in [[quantity]] or [[number]]; to increase [[greatly]].
#: {{syn|en|aggregate|amound|collect|gather|Thesaurus:accumulate}}
#* {{quote-book
|en
|year=1770
|title={{w|The Deserted Village}}
|first=Oliver|last=Goldsmith
|authorlink=Oliver Goldsmith
|lines=17–18
|passage=Ill fares the land, to hastening ills a prey, / Where wealth '''accumulates''', and men decay.
}}
# {{lb|en|education|dated}} To take a higher [[degree]] at the same time with a lower degree, or at a shorter interval than usual.

